{'content_type': 'audio_transcription', 'text': 'Materialism in Western thought has deep historical roots and has evolved through various intellectual movements. Ancient Greek philosophers like Leucippus and Democritus first proposed that everything is composed of tiny, indivisible particles (atoms) in a void. This early materialism laid the groundwork for later developments.

During the Enlightenment, philosophers like John Locke and Pierre Gassendi emphasized empirical observation and natural laws, steering away from supernatural explanations. This shift reinforced a materialist worldview, where the universe was seen as governed by physical laws and reason.

In the 19th century, Karl Marx and Friedrich Engels introduced dialectical materialism, arguing that material conditions and economic factors drive historical and social change. This perspective heavily influenced modern political and social theories.

The Enlightenment’s emphasis on reason, science, and empirical evidence further entrenched materialism, shaping modern Western thought. Over time, this perspective became foundational in the sciences and many philosophical circles, leading to the modern materialist worldview that focuses on physical reality as the basis for all phenomena.

Today, materialism underpins much of modern science and secular thought, influencing everything from economics to psychology. The focus on empirical evidence and physical explanations continues to shape how Western societies understand the world and define what is considered "good" or valuable.', 'direction': 'out', 'decoding_id': None}
